President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the State of Ohio due to severe storms, flooding, and landslides that occurred from February 5 to February 13, 2019. This declaration allows for federal assistance to supplement state and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be available for emergency work, as well as the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties of Adams, Athens, Brown, Gallia, Guernsey, Hocking, Jackson, Jefferson, Lawrence, Meigs, Monroe, Morgan, Muskingum, Noble, Perry, Pike, Ross, Scioto, Vinton, and Washington are included in the declaration. Additionally, hazard mitigation measures statewide will be eligible for federal funding on a cost-sharing basis. Steven W. Johnson has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Further designations may be made in the future if requested by the state and warranted by damage assessments. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.